ies </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Microsoft to Offer Some Cybersecurity Free After Suspected China Hack]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Company says it will make security logs available to customers with lower-cost cloud services <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065271"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819653?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Microsoft&#39;s tiered payment system drew criticism in the wake of an alleged Chinese cyber-espionage campaign.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Victor J. Blue/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065271"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dustin-volz" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dustin Volz</a></span> in Washington and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/robert-mcmillan" itemprop="url" rel="author">Robert McMillan</a></span> in San Francisco</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 19, 2023 10:24 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-to-offer-some-cybersecurity-tools-free-after-suspected-china-hack-6db94221"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">Microsoft</a> said it plans to offer free some tools that can spot cyberattacks following last week&#39;s disclosure of a major security breach linked to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-email-hack-shows-greater-sophistication-skill-of-chinas-cyberspies-7f7cff67?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Chinese hackers</a> that was undetectable for some customers.</p><p> The decision to open up access to its back-end systems that log activity on the cloud came after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">Microsoft</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> tiered payment system attracted criticism in the wake of an alleged Chinese cyber-espionage campaign, which the company said infiltrated its cloud-based email system and compromised inboxes at about two dozen organizations globally. The federal government, including officials at the State Department and Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo, was among the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-hackers-spied-on-state-department-13a09f03?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">victims of the attack</a> , US officials said.</p><p> Beginning in September, the technology company will make 31 critically important security logs available free to licensees of the company&#39;s lower-cost cloud services, including the type of email log that was used to identify the China-linked attack, said Vasu Jakkal, a vice president of security at Microsoft. The company will also increase the duration of retention for security logs from 90 to 180 days, Jakkal said.</p><p> While logs don&#39;t prevent cyberattacks, companies use them to detect and investigate hacks because the logs keep track of activity on Microsoft&#39;s servers. In the recent China-linked breach, key logging information required to detect the attack was only available to purchasers of Microsoft&#39;s top-tier Microsoft 365 cloud service, known as E5, officials said last week. That left some <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-hacking-was-undetectable-for-some-who-had-less-expensive-microsoft-services-58730629?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">customers with cheaper plans</a> no way of figuring out whether they had been hacked.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “This is a significant step forward to ensuring that every Microsoft customer has the right visibility to detect other threats that we know are targeting American organizations every day,” said Eric Goldstein, executive assistant director for cybersecurity at the US Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency.</p><p> Jakkal and Goldstein said the effort to identify valuable security logs and provide them free to Microsoft customers had been continuing for a year and was a result of collaboration between Microsoft and the Biden administration. Both declined to link Wednesday&#39;s announcement directly to the alleged China hack. But “there was clearly an urgency to get this done, given the sophistication of the landscape,” Jakkal said.</p><p> After the hack, senior Biden administration officials, a prominent Democratic senator and cybersecurity experts called on Microsoft to make computer logs of activity on the cloud more widely available. Once Microsoft became aware of the hacking campaign, which was first detected by the State Department, it was able to identify victims even if the targeted companies weren&#39;t paying for the premium service. But experts said the lack of visibility for some customers meant the attack might have gone unnoticed for a longer period.</p><p> Many companies are unaware that their cloud-computing products might come with incomplete logs, said Jake Williams, a cybersecurity consultant. “I consult with organizations regularly that only find out they are missing these logs when they have to investigate an account takeover,” Williams said.</p><p> Democratic Sen. Ron Wyden of Oregon welcomed the move but said large cybersecurity businesses like Microsoft had misaligned incentives that made it lucrative to offer insecure products and upsell customers on cybersecurity add-ons.</p><p> “It shouldn&#39;t have taken multiple disastrous hacks of federal systems for Microsoft to make essential security features standard for government customers, but better late than never,” Wyden said in a statement. “Going forward, federal agencies should insist that software contracts include security logs and other cybersecurity features, so our national security is no longer compromised by a shoddy procurement process.”</p><p> In the alleged China breach, which Microsoft said dates back to May and was detected about a month later, government officials had said they were concerned that some users of Microsoft&#39;s lower-cost cloud offerings wouldn&#39;t have been able to see the email logging information that revealed the breach.</p><p> Microsoft continues to investigate the recent alleged China breach, but to date the company hasn&#39;t explained how the hackers were able to pull it off. Goldstein said Tuesday that the federal government was continuing to investigate the hack and understand its full impact. Officials haven&#39;t formally linked the attack to Beijing, but said they have no reason to doubt Microsoft&#39;s attribution. China has denied the allegations and accused the US of engaging in pervasive cyber espionage.</p><p> “This was a sophisticated attack, and we are working closely with Microsoft and the investigation continues,” Goldstein said.</p><p> Write to Dustin Volz at <a href="mailto:dustin.volz@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dustin.volz@wsj.com</a> and Robert McMillan at <a href="mailto:robert.mcmillan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">robert.mcmillan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 14:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-to-offer-some-cybersecurity-tools-free-after-suspected-china-hack-6db94221</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-to-offer-some-cybersecurity-tools-free-after-suspected-china-hack-6db94221<author><![CDATA[Dustin VolzRobert McMillan]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>Computer Services</category><category> Cloud Computing</category><category> Business/Consumer Services</category><category>计算</category><category>Data Services</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>Usage/Consumption Statistics</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Privacy Issues/Information Security</category><category>网络犯罪/黑客攻击</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>Vasu Jakkal</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>usage</category><category> consumption statistics</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>privacy issues</category><category> information security</category><category>网络犯罪</category><category>黑客攻击</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>computer services</category><category> cloud computing</category><category> business</category><category> consumer services</category><category>计算</category><category>data services</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.K. Clinches $5 Billion EV-Battery Plant as Race for Green Investments Heats Up]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Move by Jaguar Land Rover owner Tata comes as Europe tries to attract more projects <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066091"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="587" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819833?width=860&amp;height=587" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Finished Range Rover cars are loaded on to a transporter at Tata&#39;s Jaguar Land Rover plant in the UK</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：克里斯·拉特克利夫/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066091"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-boston" itemprop="url" rel="author">William Boston</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 9:15 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The owner of Jaguar Land Rover plans to build a large battery factory in the UK to supply electric vehicles, throwing a lifeline to Britain&#39;s auto industry and highlighting the global race for green investment as carmakers shift to EVs.</p><p> Tata Group said Wednesday that it expects the plant to start delivering batteries in 2026 and supply future electric vehicles built by its JLR business, which makes Range Rover, Defender, Discovery and Jaguar cars. The Indian company said it was investing 4 billion pounds, equivalent to about $5.2 billion, in the project.</p><p> Tata&#39;s decision to build the factory in the UK comes as European governments compete for a slice of the billions of dollars that the automotive industry is investing in its shift toward electric vehicles.</p><p> Most EV batteries today are supplied by Asian manufacturers. Europe is now trying to catch up and promote the growth of a regional battery industry to secure technology and jobs, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vw-is-on-a-hunt-for-resources-to-remove-china-from-its-ev-batteries-663ee99?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">become less dependent on China.</a></p><p> The rivalry for green-tech investment—and the thousands of jobs that could come with it—has been exacerbated by the Biden administration&#39;s Inflation Reduction Act, which has attracted a number of battery projects to the US instead of Europe. That is prompting European governments to offer subsidies and other <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-sets-out-options-to-compete-with-u-s-green-subsidies-11675253742?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">incentives to lure EV and battery projects</a> .</p><p> “It&#39;s a competitive world, so everyone is trying to attract business to their shores,” Grant Shapps, the UK&#39;s energy security secretary, told BBC radio on Wednesday.</p><p> Tata had initially planned to build the plant elsewhere, Shapps said. He declined to elaborate on the amount of incentives and other financial details included in the UK&#39;s winning bid for the plant, but said: “It is large, make no bones about that.”</p><p> The British government said the planned Tata factory was a boost to the country&#39;s automotive sector that would create up to 4,000 new direct jobs, and thousands more in the wider supply chain.</p><p> Sales of fully electric vehicles in the UK rose to 152,965 in the first half of the year, an increase of 33% from a year ago, according to the European Automobile Manufacturers&#39; Association. That outpaced the 18% growth in sales of all types of vehicles during the same period.</p><p> Faraday Institution, a UK-based research institute for battery technology, has estimated that Britain&#39;s auto industry would need up to 10 large battery-cell manufacturing plants by 2040 to secure the country&#39;s place in the global EV economy.</p><p> The UK&#39;s record in winning battery investment has been patchy.</p><p> Battery startup Britishvolt fell into administration after failing to secure sufficient cash to continue operations. The failure of Britishvolt was a stark warning for the UK government, analysts said, and increased the urgency of clinching Tata&#39;s investment.</p><p> Other European countries have also been struggling to maintain investment flows into new battery manufacturing in the wake of hefty US subsidies.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/VOW" class="company-name">Volkswagen</a> earlier this year put <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/volkswagen-pivots-to-north-america-as-europe-loses-its-shine-1f26d7e5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">plans to build a battery plant in Eastern Europe on hold</a> to build a plant in Canada instead. Freyr Battery, an NYSE-listed company that is building a battery factory in Norway, abandoned starting a second European project to tap US aid to expand there instead.</p><p> Write to William Boston at <a href="mailto:william.boston@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">william.boston@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 13:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f<author><![CDATA[William Boston]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>Passenger Cars</category><category> Sports Utility Vehicles</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>Motor Vehicle Parts</category><category> Diversified Holding Companies</category><category>汽车</category><category>Business/Consumer Services</category><category>企业战略/规划</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>Capital Expenditure</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境/社会/治理</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>企业战略</category><category>规划</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>capital expenditure</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境的</category><category>社会的</category><category>治理</category><category>机动车</category><category>passenger cars</category><category> sports utility vehicles</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>motor vehicle parts</category><category> diversified holding companies</category><category>汽车</category><category>business</category><category> consumer services </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Venture Firms’ China Tech Deals Investigated by Congress Panel]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> House select committee says American firms&#39; investments contributed to China&#39;s military buildup and rights abuses <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065586"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819660?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Reps. Mike Gallagher, seated, and Raja Krishnamoorthi lead the House Select Committee on the Chinese Communist Party.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tom Williams/CQ Roll Call/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065586"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kate-okeeffe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Kate O&#39;Keeffe</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/berber-jin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Berber Jin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-venture-firms-deals-in-china-tech-investigated-by-congress-panel-710addc8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> A clutch of American venture-capital firms are being investigated by a congressional committee over their funding of Chinese tech companies—part of a push in Washington <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thechinahawkin-washington-rattling-corporate-boardrooms-a9c10117?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to scrutinize and potentially ban</a> such deals.</p><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-committee-lays-out-case-for-china-threat-ad62c611?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">House&#39;s select committee on the China threat</a> this week notified GGV Capital, GSR Ventures, Walden International and Qualcomm Ventures—the investment arm of chip company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/QCOM" class="company-name">Qualcomm</a> —that the panel is examining many of their investments in Chinese companies involved in semiconductors, artificial intelligence and quantum computing.</p><p> Those Chinese companies, the committee said, threaten US national security and have been involved in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warns-businesses-over-supply-chains-tied-to-rights-violations-in-china-11593625904" target="_blank" class="icon none">human-rights violations</a> . By extension, the American firms&#39; investments “directly contribute” to those human-rights abuses, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-military-spending-growth-to-accelerate-to-7-2-this-year-19703002" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s military modernization</a> and its effort to supplant US technological leadership, according to letters sent to the venture firms and reviewed by The Wall Street Journal.</p><p> GSR said the partners who worked on the deals in question are no longer at the firm. GGV declined to comment, while the other two firms didn&#39;t immediately respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Set up this year and formally known as the Select Committee on the Chinese Communist Party, the committee is increasingly targeting the role of American businesses in abetting <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-has-a-new-vision-for-itself-global-power-da8dc559" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beijing&#39;s superpower ambitions</a> . Its work is emblematic of a shift in thinking in the White House and on Capitol Hill that once supported US business ties with China but now <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-investment-flows-to-silicon-valley-venture-funds-11663234202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">see some investment</a> as counter to American interests.</p><p> Especially problematic are investments that may help China develop technology that could end up being used against the US in a potential military conflict or assist Beijing in building its surveillance state.</p><p> “We shouldn&#39;t be funding our own destruction,” the panel&#39;s chairman, Republican Rep. Mike Gallagher of Wisconsin, said in an interview. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="452" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819661?width=700&amp;height=452" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sequoia Capital drew the ire of Washington hawks because of a series of Chinese tech investments made by its China unit.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Josh Edelson/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The committee&#39;s top Democrat, Rep. Raja Krishnamoorthi of Illinois, said that American money and expertise shouldn&#39;t be used to enable China&#39;s “advancements in the technologies that could undermine our national security or American values.”</p><p> While the committee doesn&#39;t have lawmaking authority, it does have subpoena powers. Gallagher said the goal of the investigation is to compile a record that would help Congress pass a strong bill to restrict problematic investment in China.</p><p> The Senate is discussing an amendment filed by Sens. Bob Casey (D., Pa.) and John Cornyn (R., Texas) to a must-pass defense-policy bill that would require US investors to file notice of their investments in certain companies in China and other adversary nations. The White House is also working on an executive order on screening outbound investment in certain sectors.</p><p> Both the proposed Senate amendment and the executive order have been subject to lobbying from the business community, according to people involved in the process. As a result, the amendment lacks an earlier version&#39;s mechanism to review or block such investments.</p><p> The select committee, in its letters, gave the venture firms, all of them based in California, until July 26 to respond.</p><p> The letters called out GGV and Qualcomm Ventures for having invested in Megvii Technology and</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/20" class="">SenseTime</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> respectively. Those artificial-intelligence companies, which provide facial-recognition technology, are among 28 Chinese entities the Trump administration placed on an export blacklist in 2019, citing their roles in assisting Beijing&#39;s repression of Muslim minorities in the Xinjiang region.<p></p><p> The committee also cites in its letters Walden&#39;s investment in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/981?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Semiconductor Manufacturing International</a> Corp., or SMIC, China&#39;s largest chip maker. The US in 2020 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-blacklists-chinas-top-chip-maker-escalating-tech-fight-11608274932?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">restricted exports to SMIC</a> because of its support for the Chinese military. GSR was cited for investments in artificial intelligence and semiconductor companies.</p><p> The Chinese tech companies didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment. The Chinese embassy in Washington said “the US has politicized and weaponized economic and technological issues, seriously violating the principles of market economy.” It criticized the select committee for “spreading the &#39;China threat&#39; theory and making slanderous attacks on Communist Party of China.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="438" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819662?width=700&amp;height=438" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> SenseTime, which provides facial-recognition technology, was among 28 Chinese entities placed on an export blacklist by the Trump administration in 2019.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cfoto/NurPhoto/ZUMA Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The information the committee is seeking from the venture firms includes details of the Chinese companies they have invested in, management advice they have given and the role of the Communist Party in the companies.</p><p> Gallagher said this venture-capital probe is the first of a series of investigations that the committee plans to conduct into the relationships between the investment world and the party. A future target, Gallagher said, is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/SEQ" class="company-name">Sequoia</a> Capital.</p><p> Sequoia, a venture-capital icon for investments in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a> and TikTok owner ByteDance, drew the ire of Washington China hawks because of a series of Chinese tech investments made by its China unit. Following <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sequoia-made-a-fortune-investing-in-the-u-s-and-china-then-it-had-to-pick-one-f13e7b91?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">two years of scrutiny</a> from the White House and Capitol Hill, Sequoia in June said that the firm would break up into separate independent entities for the US, China and other areas.</p><p> While the move could insulate Sequoia&#39;s US arm from Washington policy debates, it doesn&#39;t preclude major US institutional investors from continuing to invest their money in Chinese tech companies through the Sequoia China spinoff.</p><p> Gallagher said, despite the split, he still has unanswered questions about Sequoia&#39;s decision to break up as well as its current operations.</p><p> Write to Kate O&#39;Keeffe at <a href="mailto:kathryn.okeeffe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kathryn.okeeffe@wsj.com</a> and Berber Jin at <a href="mailto:berber.jin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">berber.jin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-venture-firms-deals-in-china-tech-investigated-by-congress-panel-710addc8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-venture-firms-deals-in-china-tech-investigated-by-congress-panel-710addc8<author><![CDATA[Kate O’KeeffeBerber Jin]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>Trusts/Funds/Financial Vehicles</category><category>私人产权</category><category>Alternative Investments</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Investing/Securities</category><category> Venture Capital</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Sequoia Capital</category><category> SEQCAP.XX</category><category> Qualcomm</category><category> QCOM</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>trusts</category><category> funds</category><category> financial vehicles</category><category> private equity</category><category> alternative investments</category><category>金融服务</category><category>investing</category><category> securities</category><category> venture capital</category></item></channel></rss>